<TITLE> Brazil's high court ends political party hopping </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BRASILIA, Oct 5 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Brazil's Supreme Court ruled late on Thursday that legislators cannot change parties during their term in office, ending a common practice analysts say makes the country's political system more prone to corruption. The court ruled that mandates belonged to political parties not elected candidates. Brazilian legislators are notorious for switching allegiance frequently -- typically moving from opposition to government parties -- in search of better political and monetary prospects. So far this year, 46 representatives in the Chamber of Deputies have jumped ship. Three opposition parties, which had lost the bulk of those legislators, had asked the Supreme Court to have their congressional seats returned. These included the Brazilian Social Democracy Party and the Democratas, the two largest opposition parties. "If previously the constant changing of parties could be a good business (for politicians), that is no longer the case," said Roberto Freire, president of the Popular Socialist Party, another opposition party that filed the Supreme Court request. But the Supreme Court said the ruling would be applied only to party changes made after March 27, when Brazil's electoral court decided on the issue of party loyalty. The decision will spare President Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva from pushing a bill on party discipline that had found no consensus in Congress. Lula, who has been dogged by a series of corruption scandals involving key allies, pledged to clean up Brazilian politics in the second term he began in January. His ruling Workers' Party admitted in 2005 to having used illicit funds to pay election campaigns and is accused of having bribed congressmen to pass legislati
